President Jacob Zuma will deliver the party's plans for the year at its 105th birthday celebration at the Orlando Stadium in Soweto on Sunday. JOHANNESBURG - As the African National Congress (ANC) puts final touches to its January 8 statement, Secretary General Gwede Mantashe says the issues affecting the country will be top of the agenda.President Jacob Zuma will deliver the party's plans for the year at its 105th birthday celebration at the Orlando Stadium in Soweto on Sunday.The ruling party has given an update on the event and has outlined its plan of action for the year.Mantashe says unemployment, job creation and growing the country's economy are some of the issues the party's statement will deal with.&quot;Current issues that touch society must be the preoccupation of the ANC.&quot;Mantashe adds this is a very crucial year for the ANC and the party wants to display unity.&quot;We need to correct mistakes where we've slipped up. This is why we meet every year to talk about these things.&quot;The ANC says it expects thousands of people to attend its 105th birthday celebration at the Orlando Stadium, including ambassadors from various countries.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)